    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-04-02T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-04-02T09:00:00-05:00" n="503"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d503">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">394.31/4–251: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Acting Chairman of the United States Delegation to the
                        Torquay Conference</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Corse</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Torquay</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-04-02T14:00:00+00:00"
                            >April 2, 1951—2 p. m</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>647. After considering latest Australian offers <gloss target="#t_TAC1"
                        >TAC</gloss> voted terminate negots with Australia on grounds no basis for
                    agrmt exists. Only new item of substantial value was tin plate on which offer
                    was to place present rates in <gloss target="#t_GATT1">GATT</gloss> unbound.
                        <gloss target="#t_Del1">Del</gloss> considers tin plate “padding” by nature
                    of product. New offers covered 34 tariff subclasses. Of these, 13 were elim
                        primage<note n="1" xml:id="d503fn1">In Australia primage was a primary ad
                        valorem revenue duty laid by the Commonwealth Government upon
                        imports.</note> only; 11 were placing present rates in <gloss
                        target="#t_GATT1">GATT</gloss> but unbound; 3 were bindings present rates; 1
                    was elim primage bind present rate; 6 reductions, 2 of 12½ points, 4 of 5
                    points. Altho offers now cover about 114 tariff subclasses (request list covered
                    164) shallow cuts in both rates and preferences make offers of little benefit US
                    trade. In addition, Australia adamant refusal relinquish certain agric
                    preferences Canada and UK of importance US negots those countries.</p>
                <p>Informal feelers had indicated previously Australia not interested limited agrmt
                    without wool. Under circumstances, unanimously agreed no possibility
                    satisfactory agrmt.</p>
                <p>Sent Dept 647; repeated info Canberra unnumbered.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Corse</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
